com.martinandersson.javaee.utils

Class PhasedExecutorService

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.martinandersson.javaee.utils.PhasedExecutorService
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AutoCloseable, Executor, ExecutorService

    public class PhasedExecutorService
extends Object
implements ExecutorService, AutoCloseable
    Worker threads used by this executor service wait for each other and try to start tasks at the same time.

    Thus, a batch of tasks is executed in "pulses" or "phases", maximizing the probability of parallelism. Otherwise, phase shifting and non-synchronized starts of task execution may have a detrimental effect on the degree of effective parallelism if worker threads execute their logic at different times.

    A pulse is executed only if enough tasks has been supplied to feed all worker threads. A residue is executed as-is by free worker threads. For example, configure this service to use 5 threads, but feeding him with only 14 tasks will produce two synchronized pulses. The last 4 tasks will be executed as soon as worker threads become available.

    Supplying fewer tasks than worker threads make this executor service unable to execute a phase. Given that phases or pulses of execution is the entire purpose of this executor service, then such an input is considered an error and the batch of tasks will be rejected with an IllegalArgumentException.

    This executor service should be used sparingly by test code only and has two constraints enforcing this contract:

    1. All methods declared by Executor and ExecutorService that accept one single task will throw a UnsupportedOperationException.

    2. No batches of tasks are allowed to be executed in parallel. If one batch is already executing when another batch is supplied, an IllegalStateException will be thrown.

    The constraints leave few task-accepting methods from the ExecutorService interface left to use. The primary choice being invokeAll(Collection). However, PhasedExecutorService provide an extended API for easy submission of tasks. Some methods are particularly customized for test code, such as invokeManyTimes(Runnable, int) and invokeManyTimes(Callable, int).

    Also for the benefit of test code, the thread pool is constructed and "destroyed" for each batch of tasks executed. This makes overall memory consumption low and does not require an explicit shutdown by the client as is otherwise the case with executor services on the server-side.

    Author:
    Martin Andersson (webmaster at martinandersson.com)

      • invokeManyTimes

        public <T> List<Future<T>> invokeManyTimes(Callable<T> task,
                                           int count)
        Delegates to invokeAll(java.util.Collection).

        The argument supplied is the task supplied to this method, copied many times over into a Collection<Callable<T>> of equal size to the provided count.

        The task must be thread-safe given that it will be executed concurrently. With thread-safety, we mean a task with minimum side-effects and no mutable state. Explicit thread synchronization of the task, given the use-case of this executor service, is anti-pattern.

        Type Parameters:
        T - type of result
        Parameters:
        task - the logic to execute concurrently..
        count - ..for this many times
        Returns:
        all futures for management of the tasks and retrieval of their result
